messages.content: TOTD 1: What is easily visible on the outside may not be what is important on the inside. Ex. Grades and actually understanding
TOTD 2: Much conflict in life stems from the problem that it is much harder to take another person's perspective than it is to see our own.

TOTD 3: Religious ideas for me are more metaphorical than literal and are a guide to living not a strict dogma. There is a reason why some religions and survived, the humans who believed in them survived and passed it down.
TOTD 4: Growth takes a days, months, or even years to achieve. The fall only a couple seconds.
TOTD 5: Competition is a zero sum game that is good for the collective but destroys most individuals within the system.
TOTD 6: "Avoiding stupidity is easier than seeking brilliance" - Shane Parrish inspired by Charlie Munger
TOTD 7: This was was originally supposed to be about anti-fragility but I thought you needed this one today. **The best way to find a worthy mate is to be a worthy mate**

TOTD 8: The opposite of fragile is not robust. It is antifragile. Antifragile things gain from disorder like stressors. Fragile things break with disorder like mugs. Robust things do not care about disorder.

TOTD 9: Absense of evidence is not evidence of absense. A negative covid test does not mean you do not have any covid in your system, it means that they did not find evidence of covid in your system although you may still have it.
TOTD 10: When you know where to go, invest deeply. When you don't know much, explore broadly.
TOTD 11: Omit needless words. - The Elements of Style
TOTD 12: When decisions are reversible, take action fast. When decisions are irreversible, deliberate.
TOTD 13: It is easier to edit than to start writing.
TOTD 14: Touch is an important part of relationships between people. However, with long-distance and social distancing, touch is hard to come by.
TOTD 15: Your environment can affect your actions. If you leave candy out, you will be more likely to eat it. Change your environment to fit the habits that you want. No need for willpower.
TOTD 16: We tend to act emotionally in the present and rationalize after. When economists think people are rational. :klu1:

TOTD 17: We often mistake the proximate cause for the ultimate cause. Marriages often break over the little things. The little things are proximate causes, and the ultimate cause is a difference of opinion stemming from different interests or an inability to communicate.

TOTD 18: Most things in life are not one direction and isolated; they are autocatalytic cycles (feedback loops). We can't understand factors of a system in isolation; we must understand the system as a whole. As a result of these cycles, a small difference in the initial factors can lead to drasticly different outcomes.
These are not really facts so i will be changing them to Thoughts of the Day

TOTD 19: "All happy families are alike; each unhappy family is unhappy in its own way" - Leo Tolstoy in Anna Karenina. Similarly, All good animes are alike; each bad anime is bad in its own way - inspired by Domitrips Hong
TOTD 20: If you think you have power, go tell someone else's dog what to do.
TOTD 21: Evolution is dependent on death. For the system to survive, some individuals must die off. Similarly, if you want to think better, you have to kill your best ideas when they are wrong.
TOTD 22: The Founding Fathers did not have college degrees, you do not need one to think well either.'
TOTD 23: We remember unfinished things better than we do finished things. We crave closure.

TOTD 24: The medium of communication shapes how the communication is formed. Books meant for hard reading are not meant for audiobooks. For instance, on radio, complex words cannot be used so that the audience can understand. Radio can't be paused and rewound so they must be very articulate. On books, you can go back and reread a sentence

TOTD 25: When people are involved in a decision, they are more likely to agree to the final decision (negotiation). Similarly, when students are involved in learning, they are more likely to understand the material.
TOTD 25: Data that does not change your actions is not information. Stop collecting garbage data and noise.

TOTD 26: The lindy effect is the effect that things that have survived will tend to continue to survive later on. Ancient books that have survived will probably be continued to be read even though millions of new books come out each year and never get read past a couple months.
From wikipedia: future life expectancy of a non-perishable is proportional to current age
TOTD 26.5: Bonus! 🥸 "For whoever has will be given more, and they will have an abundance. Whoever does not have, even what they have will be taken from them." - Matthew 25:29 NIV

TOTD 27: Chess masters are able to memorize many of their games, but if the pieces could not happen in an actual chess match they are not any better than regular people at memorizing the board. Chess masters think on a higher level and chunk the information together. Novices are at the bottom level and see the individual pieces themselves. The chunking is what allows chess masters to play multiple people blindfolded.
TOTD 28 Technology both extends and amputates our senses and abilities.
TOTD 29: Know your circle of competence, where you actually know things. Find the line between known things and unknown things. Don't pose that you know things outside of your circle of competence
TOTD 30: The war on cancer by nixon was meant to be a 5 year plan. It has been almost 50 years and most cancer has still not been cured.

one example does not mean anything, but the younger generation has a strong belief that science and technology will solve all our problems yet it has a long way to go before it can accomplish that goal

TOTD 31: Having an anti rolemodel is better than having a rolemodel. Anti rolemodel is someone you don't want to become. Removal of bad things often does more good than addition of good things. Subtractive knowledge is more robust or universal than additive knowledge. Adapted from Nassim Nicholas Taleb and honorable mention to tompson for inspiring this fact.
TOTD 32: Technical civilization manipulates space through work but cannot change time. Inspired by the Sabbath by Abraham Joshua Heschel
TOTD 33: Saying that you don't do something saves making the decision every time you are offerred it.

If you are offerred drugs, saying that you don't do drugs is part of your identity and really easy to do to refuse them, even with peer pressure. If you have to decide everytime you are offered drugs, you are more likely to give in one time when you are tired and not mentally aware.

TOTD 34: If harvard actually believed their education was a good for everyone, they would increase enrollment. But all the alumni would be outraged because the value of Harvard is the exclusivity. credit to Peter Thiel.
TOTD 35: People don't know what to do with their money anymore.
*anymore
fixed
thanks @TriusHalf
TOTD 36: The only person you should be competing against is your previous self.
TOTD 37: You only get this moment once, make the most out of it.

TOTD 38: "People signal what they don't understand. 

The person who signals they’re wealthy, doesn’t understand wealth. 

The person who signals how busy they are, doesn’t get anything done." Shane Parrish
TOTD 39: Know Thyself
TOTD 40: Economics teaches static environments. Reality is variable.
TOTD 41: Economics assumes that people know what they want. The large majority of people do not know what they want.
TOTD 42: "Love without sacrifice is theft." - Nassim Nicholas Taleb in The Bed of Procrustes
TOTD 43: Work is the transformation of a medium into a different medium. This changes the properties of the system.
TOTD 44: Pleasure is a counter-irratant. Comfort is the removal of an irratant.
TOTD 45: How many legs does a dog have if you call the tail a leg?
- from abraham lincoln
Four. Calling a tail a leg doesn't make it a leg.
TOTD 46: A good book is one which you learn something new each time you read it.
TOTD 47: Crimes of the rich are not as contemptible than those of the poor.
TOTD 48: The well designed blueprint can never be as rewarding as a completed beautiful building.
TOTD 49: We are more open to talking truthfully about ourselves to strangers than people we know or even friends.
TOTD 50: "The first principle is that you must not fool yourself—and you are the easiest person to fool." - Richard Feynman

TOTD 51: If you just listen to what everyone else is telling you, you are living someone else's life, not your own.
TOTD 52: If you always fear failure, you won't ever take meaningful risks in your life.
TOTD 53: The average outcome is not your outcome
TOTD 54: Some of the best days are not the big events but the generic days that pass by. Take more photos of these days.
TOTD 55: People with skin in the game should make the decisions. Skin in the game is when people have a personal investment in the thing they are pursuing, typically they have something to lose.
Ex. Those commanding the war should at least have a son or daughter in the front lines.
Roman arhcitects used to have to sleep under their bridges so that they would die if their architecture was bad.
TOTD 56: We spend so much time online that we don't have enough time to spend with ourselves
TOTD 57: It is really easy to copy someone else's idea and really hard get everyones ideas out of your head before you actually start thinking.
TOTD 58: Writing is a good way to start thinking because you can start looking at your ideas.
TOTD 58 Bonus :) : "Academia rewards researcher who knows more and more about less and less" - Charlie Munger
TOTD 59: "Teachers should prepare the student for the student's future, not for the teacher's past." - Richard Hamming h/t James Clear

TOTD 60: People study the content of the medium but not the medium itself. The content blinds us from the medium. Ex. People study the content of online news instead of online news itself, the real cause of division.
TOTD 61: Language rules come after the language has been established, yet people teach language as if the rules were created then the words.
TOTD 62: We often lie to ourselves so we dont have to confront reality.
